> award-winning animation system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2008/10/15/spore-honored-with-2008-popular-mechanics-breakthrough-award|title=Spore Honored with 2008 Popular Mechanics Breakthrough Award|author=IGN Staff|date=15 October 2008|publisher=|accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Starbound]]''\n| 2016\n| [[Chucklefish]]\n| 2D side-scrolling planets<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/starbound-the-kotaku-review-1784846645|title=Starbound: The Kotaku Review|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|website=Kotaku|accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref> and content on them, such as dungeons and bosses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/starbounds-vault-update-adds-procedural-dungeons-procedural-bosses/|title=Starbound's Vault update adds procedural dungeons, procedural bosses|first=Tom|last=Sykes|date=18 December 2016|publisher=|accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Stardew Valley]]''\n| 2016\n| ConcernedApe\n| Cave areas<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2016/2/29/11134934/stardew-valley-steam-indie-farming-rpg-harvest-moon|title=How did indie farming sim Stardew Valley top the Steam sales chart?|author=|date=|website=polygon.com}}</ref> of increasing difficulty and loot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-10-09-stardew-valley-review|title=Stardew Valley review|author=|date=|website=eurogamer.net}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Terraria]]''\n| 2011\n| [[Re-Logic]]\n| Side-scrolling rectangular 2D world.<ref>{{cite web| title = Terraria Review, Terraria PC Review |url = http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/terraria-review/1900-6316247/ |date = May 31, 2011 |last=Mc Shea |first=Tim}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Binding of Isaac (video game)|The Binding of Isaac]]''\n| 2011\n| [[Edmund McMillen]]\n| Top-down 2D levels made up of interconnected rectangular rooms with random monsters and loot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2011/09/the-binding-of-isaac-takes-on-religion-in-a-randomly-generated-zelda-styled-roguelike/|title=The Binding of Isaac takes on religion in a randomly generated Zelda-styled Roguelike|author=|date=|website=arstechnica.com}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of roguelikes]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Timelines of video games]]\n[[Category:Video games using procedural generation| ]]\n[[Category:Video game lists by technology or feature]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Inc-vg| with [[Wikipedia:Identifying reliable sources|reliably sourced]] entries for [[Wikipedia:Notability|notable]] games}}\n\nThis is a list of video games that make at least partial use of [[procedural generation]] to create their maps and levels, or other similar features. <!--Information regarding date of release, developer, platform, genre and notability is provided when available.--> By default, the table is sorted chronologically, but the sorting factor may be selected by clicking on the small boxes next to the column headings.\n\n==List==\n===Roguelike games===\n{{see|List of roguelikes}}\nGames in the [[roguelike]] genre all have at least procedurally generated levels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/299316/7_roguelikes_that_every_developer_should_study.php|title=7 roguelikes that every developer should study|last=Fogel|first=Stefanie|website=www.gamasutra.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n|-\n! width=\"20%\"| Title\n! Year\n! width=\"20%\"| Developer(s)\n! width=\"60%\"| Procedural content\n|-\n| ''[[Banished (video game)|Banished]]''\n| 2014\n| Shining Rock Software\n| Terrain map.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-02-25-banished-review|title=Banished review|first=Paul|last=Dean|date=28 February 2014|publisher=|accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Borderlands (series)|''Borderlands'' series]]\n| 2009\u20132019\n| [[Gearbox Software]], [[2K Australia]]\n| Weapons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https: