{"title_page": "Mike Waddell (sports administrator)", "text_new": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Mike Waddell\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date =\n| birth_place = [[Hickory, North Carolina]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = [[Guilford College]] (BS)<br>[[Ohio University]] (MA)\n| admin_years1 = 2001\u20132006\n| admin_team1 = [[Akron Zips|Akron]] (assoc. AD/interim AD)\n| admin_years2 = 2006\u20132010\n| admin_team2 = [[Cincinnati Bearcats|Cincinnati]] (senior assoc. AD)\n| admin_years3 = 2010\u20132013\n| admin_team3 = [[Towson Tigers|Towson]] (Director of Athletics)\n| admin_years4 = 2013\u20132014\n| admin_team4 = [[Arkansas Razorbacks|Arkansas]] (senior assoc. AD)\n| admin_years5 = 2014\u20132016\n| admin_team5 = [[Illinois Fighting Illini|Illinois]] (senior assoc. AD)\n| admin_years6 = 2016-2018\n| admin_team6 = [[International Speedway Corporation]] (vice president)\n| admin_years7 = 2018\u20132019\n| admin_team7 = [[Orlando Apollos]] (president)\n| admin_years8 = 2019\u20132020\n| admin_team8 = [[Orlando Storm]] (president)\n| admin_years9 = 2020\u2013Present\n| admin_team9 = [[Allen Americans]] (president)(alternate governor)\n| championships = \n| awards = \n}}\n'''Mike Waddell''' is an American professional sports executive who is the President and Alternate Governor of the [[ECHL]]'s [[Allen Americans]]. He is also the [[Founder (corporate title)|Founder]] of BRENTWOOD PARTNERS, LLC, a sports consulting firm, where he is currently of counsel.\n\nPreviously Waddell was President of the [[Orlando Apollos]] of the [[Alliance of American Football]].  Along with Head Coach [[Steve Spurrier]] and General Manager [[Tim Ruskell]], Waddell was part of the leadership team that pushed the Apollos to an Alliance-best 7-1 record, and which averaged over 20,000 fans per home game at Spectrum Stadium, and sold over 5,400 season tickets. Following the AAF's folding, Waddell also worked with [[World TeamTennis]] on a contract basis through BRENTWOOD PARTNERS, LLC to provide counsel to the [[Orlando Storm]] in advance of the team's second season in 2020.\n\nWaddell relocated to Orlando in 2018 after serving as Vice President at [[Richmond Raceway]] in [[NASCAR]] from 2016 to 2018, where he oversaw the reformation of the ticketing, marketing and communications units, and founded the first-ever NASCAR track owned eSports team. <ref>{{cite news |last=Wilson |first=Steven B. |date=July 20, 2016 |title=Richmond International Raceway Names Michael Waddell Vice President of Marketing and Communications |url=https://speedwaydigest.com/index.php/news/speedway-news/32871-richmond-international-raceway-names-michael-waddell-vice-president-of-marketing-and-communications |work=Speedyay Digest |location= |access-date=February 20, 2019 }} \n</ref>  \n\nHe previously spent 28 years in college athletics, including three as the Director of Athletics at [[Towson University]] from 2010 to 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/college/bs-xpm-2010-09-28-bal-towson-mike-waddell-cincinnati-athletic-director-0928-story.html|title=Towson to name Cincinnati's Mike Waddell its new athletic director|date=September 28, 2010|agency=''[[The Baltimore Sun]]''|accessdate=January 13, 2019|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/75P57umFU|archivedate=January 13, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/baltimore-county/towson/bal-mike-waddell-leaving-towson-for-job-in-arkansas-athletic-department-20130520-story.html|title=Mike Waddell leaving Towson for job in Arkansas' athletic department|date=May 20, 2013|agency=''[[The Baltimore Sun]]''|author=Markus, Don|accessdate=January 13, 2019|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/75P5FkphD|archivedate=January 13, 2019}}</ref> \n\nEarlier in his career Waddell served in executive positions in the athletics departments at the [[University of Akron]] from 2001 to 2006, the [[University of Cincinnati]] from 2006 to 2010, the [[University of Arkansas]] from 2013 to 2014, and the [[University of Illinois]] from 2014 to 2016.  \n\nWaddell began his career in college athletics as a radio and television broadcaster at the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] from 1991 to 1994, the [[University of Virginia]] from 1994 to 1997, [[Appalachian State University]] from 1997 to 2000, and the [[United States Military Academy at West Point]] from 2000 to 2001.{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Early life, education, and family==\nWaddell was born in [[Hickory, North Carolina]] and graduated from The [[Asheville School]] in 1988. He went on to play football at [[Guilford College]] where he earned his bachelor's degree in sports management in 1991.  Waddell continued his education later in his career at [[Ohio University]] where he completed a master's degree in sports administration in 2010.<ref>[https://towsontigers.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=1683]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nWaddell made the transition to pro sports in 2018 when he was named President of the [[Orlando Apollos]] of the [[Alliance of American Football]] (AAF) on August 4, 2018 and remained in this position until the AAF ceased operations in April, 2019. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/os-orlando-alliance-of-american-football-president-0828-story.html|access-date=August 28, 2018|title=Alliance of American Football taps Richmond Raceway exec as Orlando's president|newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|first=Stephen|last=Ruiz|date=August 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/sports/illini-sports/baseball/2019-02-20/asmussen-ex-ui-administrator-fights-boost-aaf-helm-apollos|title=Ex-UI administrator fights to boost AAF at helm of Apollos|date=February 20, 2019|agency=''[[The News-Gazette (Champaign\u2013Urbana)|The News-Gazette]]''|author=Asmussen, Bob|accessdate=February 21, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/76M519jZw|archivedate=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, 2020 Waddell agreed to terms with the [[ECHL]]'s [[Allen Americans]] to become their President & Alternate Governor.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [https://www.brentwood.partners]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://towsontigers.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=1683 Towson profile]\n* [http://www.brentwood.partners Brentwood Partners Website]\n* [http://www.orlandostorm.com Orlando Storm Website]\n* [http://www.i4biz.com/sports/a-winning-formula/  I4 Business Magazine Profile]\n*\u00a0[https://wnst.net/towson-tigers/towson-gives-ad-waddell-contract-extension/ Waddell Receives Contract Extension]\n*\u00a0[http://defiantlydutch.blogspot.com/2012/02/towson-looks-back-as-well-as-forward-as.html Towson Athletics Turnaround]\n\n\n{{Akron Zips athletic director navbox}}\n{{Towson Tigers athletic director navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Waddell, Michael P.}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Akron Zips athletic directors]]\n[[Category:NASCAR people]]\n[[Category:Towson Tigers athletic directors]]\n[[Category:Guilford College alumni]]\n[[Category:Ohio University alumni]]\n[[Category:Orlando Apollos]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Mike Waddell\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date =\n| birth_place = [[Hickory, North Carolina]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = [[Guilford College]] (BS)<br>[[Ohio University]] (MA)\n| admin_years1 = 2001\u20132006\n| admin_team1 = [[Akron Zips|Akron]] (assoc. AD/interim AD)\n| admin_years2 = 2006\u20132010\n| admin_team2 = [[Cincinnati Bearcats|Cincinnati]] (senior assoc. AD)\n| admin_years3 = 2010\u20132013\n| admin_team3 = [[Towson Tigers|Towson]] (Director of Athletics)\n| admin_years4 = 2013\u20132014\n| admin_team4 = [[Arkansas Razorbacks|Arkansas]] (senior assoc. AD)\n| admin_years5 = 2014\u20132016\n| admin_team5 = [[Illinois Fighting Illini|Illinois]] (senior assoc. AD)\n| admin_years6 = 2016-2018\n| admin_team6 = [[International Speedway Corporation]] (vice president)\n| admin_years7 = 2018\u20132019\n| admin_team7 = [[Orlando Apollos]] (president)\n| admin_years8 = 2019\u20132020\n| admin_team8 = [[Orlando Storm]] (president)\n| admin_years8 = 2020\u2013Present\n| admin_team8 = [[Allen Americans]] (president)(alternate governor)\n| championships = \n| awards = \n}}\n'''Mike Waddell''' is an American professional sports executive who is the President and Alternate Governor of the [[ECHL]]'s [[Allen Americans]]. He is also the [[Founder (corporate title)|Founder]] of BRENTWOOD PARTNERS, LLC, a sports consulting firm, where he is currently of counsel.\n\nPreviously Waddell was President of the [[Orlando Apollos]] of the [[Alliance of American Football]].  Along with Head Coach [[Steve Spurrier]] and General Manager [[Tim Ruskell]], Waddell was part of the leadership team that pushed the Apollos to an Alliance-best 7-1 record, and which averaged over 20,000 fans per home game at Spectrum Stadium, and sold over 5,400 season tickets. Following the AAF's folding, Waddell also worked with [[World TeamTennis]] on a contract basis through BRENTWOOD PARTNERS, LLC to provide counsel to the [[Orlando Storm]] in advance of the team's second season in 2020.\n\nWaddell relocated to Orlando in 2018 after serving as Vice President at [[Richmond Raceway]] in [[NASCAR]] from 2016 to 2018, where he oversaw the reformation of the ticketing, marketing and communications units, and founded the first-ever NASCAR track owned eSports team. <ref>{{cite news |last=Wilson |first=Steven B. |date=July 20, 2016 |title=Richmond International Raceway Names Michael Waddell Vice President of Marketing and Communications |url=https://speedwaydigest.com/index.php/news/speedway-news/32871-richmond-international-raceway-names-michael-waddell-vice-president-of-marketing-and-communications |work=Speedyay Digest |location= |access-date=February 20, 2019 }} \n</ref>  \n\nHe previously spent 28 years in college athletics, including three as the Director of Athletics at [[Towson University]] from 2010 to 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/college/bs-xpm-2010-09-28-bal-towson-mike-waddell-cincinnati-athletic-director-0928-story.html|title=Towson to name Cincinnati's Mike Waddell its new athletic director|date=September 28, 2010|agency=''[[The Baltimore Sun]]''|accessdate=January 13, 2019|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/75P57umFU|archivedate=January 13, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/baltimore-county/towson/bal-mike-waddell-leaving-towson-for-job-in-arkansas-athletic-department-20130520-story.html|title=Mike Waddell leaving Towson for job in Arkansas' athletic department|date=May 20, 2013|agency=''[[The Baltimore Sun]]''|author=Markus, Don|accessdate=January 13, 2019|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/75P5FkphD|archivedate=January 13, 2019}}</ref> \n\nEarlier in his career Waddell served in executive positions in the athletics departments at the [[University of Akron]] from 2001 to 2006, the [[University of Cincinnati]] from 2006 to 2010, the [[University of Arkansas]] from 2013 to 2014, and the [[University of Illinois]] from 2014 to 2016.  \n\nWaddell began his career in college athletics as a radio and television broadcaster at the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] from 1991 to 1994, the [[University of Virginia]] from 1994 to 1997, [[Appalachian State University]] from 1997 to 2000, and the [[United States Military Academy at West Point]] from 2000 to 2001.{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Early life, education, and family==\nWaddell was born in [[Hickory, North Carolina]] and graduated from The [[Asheville School]] in 1988. He went on to play football at [[Guilford College]] where he earned his bachelor's degree in sports management in 1991.  Waddell continued his education later in his career at [[Ohio University]] where he completed a master's degree in sports administration in 2010.<ref>[https://towsontigers.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=1683]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nWaddell made the transition to pro sports in 2018 when he was named President of the [[Orlando Apollos]] of the [[Alliance of American Football]] (AAF) on August 4, 2018 and remained in this position until the AAF ceased operations in April, 2019. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/os-orlando-alliance-of-american-football-president-0828-story.html|access-date=August 28, 2018|title=Alliance of American Football taps Richmond Raceway exec as Orlando's president|newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|first=Stephen|last=Ruiz|date=August 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/sports/illini-sports/baseball/2019-02-20/asmussen-ex-ui-administrator-fights-boost-aaf-helm-apollos|title=Ex-UI administrator fights to boost AAF at helm of Apollos|date=February 20, 2019|agency=''[[The News-Gazette (Champaign\u2013Urbana)|The News-Gazette]]''|author=Asmussen, Bob|accessdate=February 21, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/76M519jZw|archivedate=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, 2020 Waddell agreed to terms with the [[ECHL]]'s [[Allen Americans]] to become their President & Alternate Governor.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [https://www.brentwood.partners]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://towsontigers.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=1683 Towson profile]\n* [http://www.brentwood.partners Brentwood Partners Website]\n* [http://www.orlandostorm.com Orlando Storm Website]\n* [http://www.i4biz.com/sports/a-winning-formula/  I4 Business Magazine Profile]\n*\u00a0[https://wnst.net/towson-tigers/towson-gives-ad-waddell-contract-extension/ Waddell Receives Contract Extension]\n*\u00a0[http://defiantlydutch.blogspot.com/2012/02/towson-looks-back-as-well-as-forward-as.html Towson Athletics Turnaround]\n\n\n{{Akron Zips athletic director navbox}}\n{{Towson Tigers athletic director navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Waddell, Michael P.}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Akron 